Note:
HIR to COBOL Backend - Generates idiomatic COBOL code from HIR

This file provides complete HIR → COBOL code generation for the Translation
universal language translator. Generates production-quality COBOL-85 code.

Features:
- Complete HIR → COBOL translation
- Four divisions (IDENTIFICATION, ENVIRONMENT, DATA, PROCEDURE)
- Data definitions with level numbers and PICTURE clauses
- All COBOL statements with proper formatting
- Idiomatic COBOL-85 output
- Proper indentation (4 spaces)
- Uppercase keywords (COBOL convention)
- Statement terminators (periods)
- Free-format COBOL output

Dependencies:
- compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/cobol/cobol_emitter.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/containers/dictionary.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/containers/list.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/cobol/cobol_emitter.runa" as Emitter
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListOps

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Code Generation Context
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Bundles every piece of mutable state the COBOL code-gen pass needs: the byte
emitter, the indent cursor, an arena handle so per-translation temps can be
released in O(1), and a list of error records consumed by the caller.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four int64 slots, total 32 bytes (see CONTEXT_SIZE). Allocation and teardown
live in create_cobol_gen_context / destroy_cobol_gen_context; this Type only
declares the layout.
@End Implementation

Type called "COBOLGenContext":
    emitter as Integer          Note: COBOL emitter for output
    indent_level as Integer     Note: Current indentation level
    arena as Integer            Note: Arena for allocations
    errors as Integer           Note: Error list
End Type

Constant CONTEXT_SIZE as Integer is 32  Note: 4 fields × 8 bytes

@Reasoning:
A code-gen pass cannot emit a single byte until its context is fully wired:
emitter live, indent zeroed, arena bound, error list allocated. Building all
of that here removes a class of "half-initialised context" bugs from the
caller side.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates CONTEXT_SIZE bytes, constructs a COBOL emitter, then writes
emitter/indent/arena/errors slots via memory_set_int64. Frees the partial
allocation if emitter construction fails so callers see a clean 0 on failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_cobol_gen_context" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create COBOL code generation context

    @Reasoning:
    Context tracks emitter for output, indentation level for formatting,
    arena for memory, and errors for diagnostics.
    @End Reasoning

    Let context be proc allocate from Layout with CONTEXT_SIZE

    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let emitter be proc create_cobol_emitter from Emitter

    If emitter is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with context
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 0, emitter
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, 0    Note: indent_level
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 16, arena

    Let errors be proc create_list from ListOps
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 24, errors

    Return context
End Process

@Reasoning:
Releases every owned subresource (emitter, errors list) before freeing the
context block, in the inverse order they were created. Null-tolerant so the
caller can invoke it on any cleanup path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Pulls the emitter and errors pointers from slots 0 and 24, calls their
destroyers only when non-zero, then deallocates the context. The arena slot
is not owned, only borrowed, so it is not freed here.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_cobol_gen_context" takes context as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy COBOL code generation context

    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    If emitter is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy_cobol_emitter from Emitter with emitter
    End If

    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 24
    If errors is not equal to 0:
        proc destroy_list from ListOps with errors
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with context

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Translation Entry Point
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public entry point - the only function the translation driver calls. It owns
the context's lifetime so the rest of the file can assume context is valid
when reached.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Validates the hir pointer, builds a COBOLGenContext through
create_cobol_gen_context, dispatches generate_node on the root, then reads
the accumulated text from the emitter via get_output before destroying the
context.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
One context create / destroy per file. The output buffer lifetime extends
past the context because get_output returns a caller-owned string.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "translate_hir_to_cobol" takes hir as Integer, arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Main entry point for HIR → COBOL translation

    @Reasoning:
    Create generation context, generate COBOL code from HIR,
    retrieve output, clean up context, return COBOL source code.
    @End Reasoning

    If hir is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let context be proc create_cobol_gen_context from arena

    If context is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc generate_node with context, hir

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let output be proc get_output from Emitter with emitter

    proc destroy_cobol_gen_context from context

    Return output
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Node Generation Dispatcher
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Central dispatcher driving the rest of the file. Each HIR node carries a
_type tag (set by the lowering layer); this routine looks up that tag and
hands the work to the matching generate_* helper. Centralising dispatch
keeps the generators ignorant of one another.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the "_type" dictionary slot of the HIR node, then runs a chain of
string_equals comparisons against the supported COBOL node tags (program,
divisions, sections, statements, expressions). Returns 1 (no-op) for null
input so traversal code does not need null checks at every call site.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Sequential equality scan; acceptable because the number of node kinds is
fixed and small relative to traversal depth. A hashed dispatch is a future
optimisation.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "generate_node" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate COBOL code for HIR node

    @Reasoning:
    Dispatcher function that checks HIR node type and delegates to
    specific generation function.
    @End Reasoning

    If hir is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let node_type be proc get_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "_type"

    If node_type is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Program Structure
    Let match be proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_program"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_program with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_identification_division"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_identification_division with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_environment_division"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_environment_division with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_data_division"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_data_division with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_procedure_division"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_procedure_division with context, hir
    End If

    Note: Data Division Components
    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_file_section"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_file_section with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_working_storage"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_working_storage with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_linkage_section"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_linkage_section with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_data_item"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_data_item with context, hir
    End If

    Note: Environment Division Components
    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_configuration_section"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_config_section with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_input_output_section"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_input_output_section with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_select"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_select_statement with context, hir
    End If

    Note: Procedure Division Components
    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_section"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_section with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_paragraph"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_paragraph with context, hir
    End If

    Note: Statements
    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_move"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_move_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_add"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_add_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_subtract"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_subtract_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_multiply"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_multiply_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_divide"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_divide_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_compute"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_compute_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_if"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_if_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_evaluate"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_evaluate_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_perform"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_perform_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_display"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_display_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_accept"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_accept_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_goto"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_goto_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_stop"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_stop_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_exit"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_exit_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_return"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_goback_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_call"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_call_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Note: File I/O
    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_open"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_open_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_close"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_close_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_read"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_read_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_write"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_write_stmt with context, hir
    End If

    Note: Expressions
    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_identifier"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_identifier with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_literal"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_literal with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_arithmetic_expr"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_arithmetic_expr with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_relational_expr"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_relational_expr with context, hir
    End If

    Set match to proc string_equals with node_type, "cobol_figurative_constant"
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return proc generate_figurative_const with context, hir
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Program Structure Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
COBOL programs are partitioned into divisions; emitting them in source order
preserves the COBOL-85 layout the downstream compiler expects.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the "divisions" list off the HIR program node, walks it linearly and
recurses through generate_node so each division emits itself.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_program" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate COBOL program

    @Reasoning:
    COBOL program consists of four divisions. Generate each division
    in order: IDENTIFICATION, ENVIRONMENT, DATA, PROCEDURE.
    @End Reasoning

    Let divisions be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "divisions"

    If divisions is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with divisions
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than count:
        Let division be proc get_list_item from ListOps with divisions, i
        proc generate_node with context, division
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The IDENTIFICATION DIVISION is mandatory and carries PROGRAM-ID, which the
COBOL compiler needs to bind external linkage names. Missing it would cause
downstream tools to reject the source.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "IDENTIFICATION DIVISION." via emit_division_header, then if the HIR
node carries a program_id string, writes "    PROGRAM-ID. <id>." at indent
level 1 followed by a blank line.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_identification_division" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate IDENTIFICATION DIVISION

    @Reasoning:
    IDENTIFICATION DIVISION structure:
    IDENTIFICATION DIVISION.
    PROGRAM-ID. program-name.
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    proc emit_division_header from Emitter with emitter, "IDENTIFICATION"

    Let program_id be proc get_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "program_id"

    If program_id is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, 1
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "PROGRAM-ID"
        proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, program_id
        proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
        proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter
    End If

    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
ENVIRONMENT DIVISION is where I/O assignments and runtime config live; even
when empty the header must appear so subsequent divisions are not misparsed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Writes the division header, then walks the "sections" list and dispatches
each via generate_node. A trailing blank line separates this division from
the next.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_environment_division" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate ENVIRONMENT DIVISION

    @Reasoning:
    ENVIRONMENT DIVISION contains configuration and file control sections.
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    proc emit_division_header from Emitter with emitter, "ENVIRONMENT"

    Let sections be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "sections"

    If sections is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with sections
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than count:
            Let section be proc get_list_item from ListOps with sections, i
            proc generate_node with context, section
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
DATA DIVISION carries every record, working-storage variable and linkage
parameter the procedure division will reference. Generating it before the
procedure division matches the COBOL section ordering.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits the division header, then iterates the "sections" list (FILE,
WORKING-STORAGE, LINKAGE in that order) and recurses through generate_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_data_division" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate DATA DIVISION

    @Reasoning:
    DATA DIVISION contains data definitions in sections
    (FILE, WORKING-STORAGE, LINKAGE).
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    proc emit_division_header from Emitter with emitter, "DATA"

    Let sections be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "sections"

    If sections is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with sections
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than count:
            Let section be proc get_list_item from ListOps with sections, i
            proc generate_node with context, section
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
PROCEDURE DIVISION carries the executable statements of a COBOL program.
This is the last of the four mandatory divisions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits the division header then walks the "body" list, dispatching each
paragraph or section through generate_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_procedure_division" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate PROCEDURE DIVISION

    @Reasoning:
    PROCEDURE DIVISION contains executable code in sections and paragraphs.
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    proc emit_division_header from Emitter with emitter, "PROCEDURE"

    Let body be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "body"

    If body is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with body
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than count:
            Let item be proc get_list_item from ListOps with body, i
            proc generate_node with context, item
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Data Division Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
FILE SECTION declares record buffers tied to SELECT statements; without it
COBOL cannot bind file I/O to a named record.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits the section header "FILE SECTION." then iterates the "items" list and
recurses through generate_node for each contained data item.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_file_section" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate FILE SECTION

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    proc emit_section_header from Emitter with emitter, "FILE"

    Let items be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "items"

    If items is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with items
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than count:
            Let item be proc get_list_item from ListOps with items, i
            proc generate_node with context, item
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
WORKING-STORAGE holds module-local variables that survive across paragraph
calls. Generated before LINKAGE because the procedure division references
both but COBOL requires this order.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Writes the WORKING-STORAGE header, walks "items" via generate_node so each
data item emits its own level number, name, PIC clause and VALUE clause.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_working_storage" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate WORKING-STORAGE SECTION

    @Reasoning:
    WORKING-STORAGE contains variable declarations with level numbers
    and PICTURE clauses.
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    proc emit_section_header from Emitter with emitter, "WORKING-STORAGE"

    Let items be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "items"

    If items is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with items
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than count:
            Let item be proc get_list_item from ListOps with items, i
            proc generate_node with context, item
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
LINKAGE SECTION declares parameter records the caller passes in via CALL ...
USING. Required whenever the program is invoked as a sub-program.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits the LINKAGE header then walks the "items" list, recursing into
generate_node for each parameter record.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_linkage_section" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate LINKAGE SECTION

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    proc emit_section_header from Emitter with emitter, "LINKAGE"

    Let items be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "items"

    If items is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with items
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than count:
            Let item be proc get_list_item from ListOps with items, i
            proc generate_node with context, item
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
A COBOL data item declaration must follow strict ordering: level, name, PIC,
VALUE. Emitting fragments independently lets callers skip clauses absent
from the HIR (e.g. a group item with no PIC).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads level, name, picture and value strings from the HIR node dictionary
and emits each clause with a separating space if present. Closes the line
with a period and newline. Indented one level to match COBOL convention.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_data_item" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate data item (level number + name + PICTURE + VALUE)

    @Reasoning:
    COBOL data item format:
    level-number data-name PIC picture-string VALUE literal.
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, 1

    Note: Emit level number
    Let level be proc get_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "level"
    If level is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, level
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
    End If

    Note: Emit data name
    Let name be proc get_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "name"
    If name is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, name
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
    End If

    Note: Emit PICTURE clause
    Let picture be proc get_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "picture"
    If picture is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "PIC"
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, picture
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
    End If

    Note: Emit VALUE clause
    Let value be proc get_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "value"
    If value is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "VALUE"
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, value
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
    End If

    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Environment Division Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
CONFIGURATION SECTION supplies SOURCE/OBJECT-COMPUTER paragraphs and other
compile-time settings. The header alone is sufficient when the HIR node
carries no sub-paragraphs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Writes the section header through emit_section_header so subsequent
emitters can append paragraphs after the section opens.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_config_section" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate CONFIGURATION SECTION

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    proc emit_section_header from Emitter with emitter, "CONFIGURATION"

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
INPUT-OUTPUT SECTION is where FILE-CONTROL lives; without it SELECT clauses
have no enclosing section and COBOL parsers reject the source.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Writes the INPUT-OUTPUT header, then emits FILE-CONTROL and iterates the
HIR "files" list, recursing for each SELECT through generate_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_input_output_section" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate INPUT-OUTPUT SECTION

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    proc emit_section_header from Emitter with emitter, "INPUT-OUTPUT"

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "FILE-CONTROL"
    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Let files be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "files"

    If files is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with files
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than count:
            Let file be proc get_list_item from ListOps with files, i
            proc generate_node with context, file
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
SELECT binds a logical file name to a physical resource. The HIR layer only
carries one file name, so the same identifier is reused as the assign target
with a ".DAT" suffix - a defensible default when the source omits explicit
ASSIGN data.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Indented two levels under INPUT-OUTPUT > FILE-CONTROL. Emits "SELECT <name>
ASSIGN TO <name>.DAT." Reads file_name from the HIR dictionary.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_select_statement" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate SELECT statement

    @Reasoning:
    SELECT file-name ASSIGN TO external-name.
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, 2
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "SELECT"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter

    Let file_name be proc get_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "file_name"
    If file_name is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, file_name
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
    End If

    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "ASSIGN TO"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
    If file_name is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, file_name
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, ".DAT"
    End If

    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Procedure Division Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A SECTION groups paragraphs in PROCEDURE DIVISION so PERFORM ... THRU can
target an inclusive range. The section header must be written before its
contained paragraphs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "<name> SECTION." then walks the "paragraphs" list, dispatching each
via generate_node.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_section" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate SECTION

    @Reasoning:
    COBOL section: section-name SECTION. paragraphs.
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    Let name be proc get_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "name"
    If name is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, name
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, " SECTION"
        proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
        proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter
    End If

    Let paragraphs be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "paragraphs"

    If paragraphs is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with paragraphs
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than count:
            Let para be proc get_list_item from ListOps with paragraphs, i
            proc generate_node with context, para
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
A paragraph is the smallest PERFORM target in COBOL; the header line and
statement body must appear consecutively or the parser will associate
statements with the previous paragraph.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "<name>." through emit_paragraph_header, walks the "statements" list
through generate_node, and ends with a blank line for readability.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_paragraph" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate PARAGRAPH

    @Reasoning:
    COBOL paragraph: paragraph-name. statements.
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    Let name be proc get_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "name"
    If name is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_paragraph_header from Emitter with emitter, name
    End If

    Let statements be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "statements"

    If statements is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with statements
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than count:
            Let stmt be proc get_list_item from ListOps with statements, i
            proc generate_node with context, stmt
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Statement Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
MOVE is COBOL's assignment primitive. Multi-destination moves let a single
source update several variables, so the destinations slot is a list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Indents one level past current indent_level, writes "MOVE", recurses on the
source expression, writes " TO ", then walks the destination list emitting
each through generate_node separated by spaces. Closes with a period and
newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_move_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate MOVE statement

    @Reasoning:
    MOVE source TO destination1 destination2 ...
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "MOVE"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter

    Let source be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "source"
    If source is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_node with context, source
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
    End If

    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "TO"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter

    Let destinations be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "destinations"

    If destinations is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with destinations
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than count:
            Let dest be proc get_list_item from ListOps with destinations, i
            proc generate_node with context, dest

            If i plus 1 is less than count:
                proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
ADD takes a list of operands; emitting them space-separated matches the
COBOL-85 "ADD a b c TO d" form. Implicit destination is handled by the
HIR layer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Indents one level past current depth, emits "ADD ", iterates the operands
list dispatching each via generate_node with spaces between, then closes
with period and newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_add_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate ADD statement

    @Reasoning:
    ADD operand1 operand2 TO destination GIVING result.
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "ADD"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter

    Let operands be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "operands"

    If operands is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with operands
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than count:
            Let operand be proc get_list_item from ListOps with operands, i
            proc generate_node with context, operand

            If i plus 1 is less than count:
                proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
SUBTRACT supports a list of subtrahends, optional GIVING for non-mutating
form, ROUNDED for fixed-point rounding, and ON SIZE ERROR for overflow
handling. Each branch is independently optional in the HIR.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "SUBTRACT " followed by space-separated subtrahends, " FROM " plus
minuend, optionally " GIVING <target>", optionally " ROUNDED". When an
on_size_error block is present, emits a newline, bumps indent to write
nested statements, restores the indent, and finally writes period + newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_subtract_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate SUBTRACT statement

    @Reasoning:
    SUBTRACT x y FROM z [GIVING w] [ROUNDED] [ON SIZE ERROR stmts].
    Read HIR structure:
    - subtrahends: list of operands to subtract
    - from_operand: minuend
    - giving_target: optional result target
    - rounded: boolean flag
    - on_size_error: optional error handler statements
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "SUBTRACT"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter

    Note: Emit subtrahends
    Let subtrahends be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "subtrahends"
    If subtrahends is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with subtrahends
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let operand be proc get_list_item from ListOps with subtrahends, i
            If operand is not equal to 0:
                proc generate_node with context, operand
                If i is less than count minus 1:
                    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
                End If
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Emit FROM
    Let from_operand be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "from_operand"
    If from_operand is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "FROM"
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc generate_node with context, from_operand
    End If

    Note: Check for GIVING
    Let giving_target be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "giving_target"
    If giving_target is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "GIVING"
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc generate_node with context, giving_target
    End If

    Note: Check for ROUNDED
    Let rounded be proc get_dict_bool_value from Dict with hir, "rounded"
    If rounded is equal to 1:
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "ROUNDED"
    End If

    Note: Check for ON SIZE ERROR
    Let error_stmts be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "on_size_error"
    If error_stmts is not equal to 0:
        Let error_count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with error_stmts
        If error_count is greater than 0:
            proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
            proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "ON SIZE ERROR"
            proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

            Note: Increment indent for error statements
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, indent_level plus 1

            Set i to 0
            While i is less than error_count:
                Let stmt be proc get_list_item from ListOps with error_stmts, i
                proc generate_node with context, stmt
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While

            Note: Restore indent
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, indent_level
            proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
        End If
    End If

    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
MULTIPLY's COBOL form is "MULTIPLY x BY y [GIVING z] [ROUNDED] [ON SIZE
ERROR ...]". Unlike ADD, the two arithmetic operands have fixed roles so
they cannot share a list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "MULTIPLY <multiplicand>", then " BY <multiplier>", then optional
" GIVING <target>", optional " ROUNDED", and optional ON SIZE ERROR block
following the same nested-indent pattern used by subtract/divide.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_multiply_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate MULTIPLY statement

    @Reasoning:
    MULTIPLY x BY y [GIVING z] [ROUNDED] [ON SIZE ERROR stmts].
    Read HIR structure:
    - multiplicand: first operand
    - multiplier: BY operand
    - giving_target: optional result target
    - rounded: boolean flag
    - on_size_error: optional error handler statements
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "MULTIPLY"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter

    Note: Emit multiplicand
    Let multiplicand be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "multiplicand"
    If multiplicand is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_node with context, multiplicand
    End If

    Note: Emit BY
    Let multiplier be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "multiplier"
    If multiplier is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "BY"
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc generate_node with context, multiplier
    End If

    Note: Check for GIVING
    Let giving_target be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "giving_target"
    If giving_target is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "GIVING"
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc generate_node with context, giving_target
    End If

    Note: Check for ROUNDED
    Let rounded be proc get_dict_bool_value from Dict with hir, "rounded"
    If rounded is equal to 1:
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "ROUNDED"
    End If

    Note: Check for ON SIZE ERROR
    Let error_stmts be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "on_size_error"
    If error_stmts is not equal to 0:
        Let error_count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with error_stmts
        If error_count is greater than 0:
            proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
            proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "ON SIZE ERROR"
            proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

            Note: Increment indent for error statements
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, indent_level plus 1

            Let i be 0
            While i is less than error_count:
                Let stmt be proc get_list_item from ListOps with error_stmts, i
                proc generate_node with context, stmt
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While

            Note: Restore indent
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, indent_level
            proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
        End If
    End If

    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
DIVIDE adds REMAINDER on top of the SUBTRACT/MULTIPLY pattern, which forces
a dedicated emitter even though most clauses share structure.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "DIVIDE <dividend> BY <divisor>" then optional GIVING, REMAINDER,
ROUNDED, and ON SIZE ERROR clauses (with nested-indent statements when
present), followed by period + newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_divide_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate DIVIDE statement

    @Reasoning:
    DIVIDE x INTO/BY y [GIVING z] [REMAINDER w] [ROUNDED] [ON SIZE ERROR stmts].
    Read HIR structure:
    - dividend: first operand
    - divisor: INTO/BY operand
    - giving_target: optional result target
    - remainder_target: optional remainder target
    - rounded: boolean flag
    - on_size_error: optional error handler statements
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "DIVIDE"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter

    Note: Emit dividend
    Let dividend be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "dividend"
    If dividend is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_node with context, dividend
    End If

    Note: Emit INTO or BY keyword and divisor
    Let divisor be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "divisor"
    If divisor is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "BY"
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc generate_node with context, divisor
    End If

    Note: Check for GIVING
    Let giving_target be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "giving_target"
    If giving_target is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "GIVING"
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc generate_node with context, giving_target
    End If

    Note: Check for REMAINDER
    Let remainder_target be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "remainder_target"
    If remainder_target is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "REMAINDER"
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc generate_node with context, remainder_target
    End If

    Note: Check for ROUNDED
    Let rounded be proc get_dict_bool_value from Dict with hir, "rounded"
    If rounded is equal to 1:
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "ROUNDED"
    End If

    Note: Check for ON SIZE ERROR
    Let error_stmts be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "on_size_error"
    If error_stmts is not equal to 0:
        Let error_count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with error_stmts
        If error_count is greater than 0:
            proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
            proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "ON SIZE ERROR"
            proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

            Note: Increment indent for error statements
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, indent_level plus 1

            Let i be 0
            While i is less than error_count:
                Let stmt be proc get_list_item from ListOps with error_stmts, i
                proc generate_node with context, stmt
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While

            Note: Restore indent
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, indent_level
            proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
        End If
    End If

    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
COMPUTE is COBOL's general-purpose arithmetic assignment, used when a single
combined arithmetic expression is easier than chaining ADD/SUBTRACT.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "COMPUTE <result> = <expression>." Both sides recurse through
generate_node so the expression subtree can be an arithmetic or relational
node.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_compute_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate COMPUTE statement

    @Reasoning:
    COMPUTE result = expression.
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "COMPUTE"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter

    Let result be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "result"
    If result is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_node with context, result
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
    End If

    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "="
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter

    Let expression be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "expression"
    If expression is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_node with context, expression
    End If

    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
COBOL-85's scoped IF requires explicit END-IF; emitting it lets the THEN and
ELSE branches contain multiple statements without dangling-else ambiguity.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Writes "IF <condition>" then a newline, bumps indent, walks then_statements,
optionally emits "ELSE" then walks else_statements, restores the indent,
and closes with "END-IF.".
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_if_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate IF statement

    @Reasoning:
    IF condition
        statements
    ELSE
        statements
    END-IF.
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "IF"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter

    Let condition be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "condition"
    If condition is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_node with context, condition
    End If

    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Note: Increment indent for THEN statements
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, indent_level plus 1

    Let then_stmts be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "then_statements"

    If then_stmts is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with then_stmts
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than count:
            Let stmt be proc get_list_item from ListOps with then_stmts, i
            proc generate_node with context, stmt
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Check for ELSE clause
    Let else_stmts be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "else_statements"

    If else_stmts is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "ELSE"
        proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

        Set count to proc get_list_length from ListOps with else_stmts
        Set i to 0

        While i is less than count:
            Set stmt to proc get_list_item from ListOps with else_stmts, i
            proc generate_node with context, stmt
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Restore indent level
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, indent_level

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "END-IF"
    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
EVALUATE is COBOL's structured switch. Emitting WHEN clauses in source
order matches the COBOL-85 first-match semantics so behavior is preserved.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Writes "EVALUATE <test_expression>", iterates when_clauses dispatching each
through generate_when_clause, then closes with "END-EVALUATE.".
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_evaluate_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate EVALUATE statement

    @Reasoning:
    EVALUATE expression
        WHEN value1 statements
        WHEN value2 statements
        WHEN OTHER statements
    END-EVALUATE.
    Read HIR structure:
    - test_expression: expression to evaluate
    - when_clauses: list of WHEN clauses with values and statements
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "EVALUATE"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter

    Note: Emit test expression
    Let test_expr be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "test_expression"
    If test_expr is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_node with context, test_expr
    End If

    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Note: Emit WHEN clauses
    Let when_clauses be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "when_clauses"
    If when_clauses is not equal to 0:
        Let clause_count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with when_clauses
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than clause_count:
            Let when_clause be proc get_list_item from ListOps with when_clauses, i
            If when_clause is not equal to 0:
                proc generate_when_clause with context, when_clause
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "END-EVALUATE"
    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
WHEN clauses pair a list of matching values (or OTHER) with an indented
statement block. Multiple values on one clause form an inclusive disjunction.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "WHEN OTHER" when the is_other flag is set; otherwise walks the
"values" list and dispatches each through generate_node, separated by
spaces. Then increments indent, walks the "statements" list, and restores
the indent.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_when_clause" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate WHEN clause for EVALUATE statement

    @Reasoning:
    WHEN clause structure:
        WHEN value1 value2
            statements
        WHEN OTHER
            statements
    Read HIR structure:
    - is_other: boolean flag for WHEN OTHER
    - values: list of values to match (if not OTHER)
    - statements: list of statements to execute
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "WHEN"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter

    Note: Check if this is WHEN OTHER
    Let is_other be proc get_dict_bool_value from Dict with hir, "is_other"
    If is_other is equal to 1:
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "OTHER"

    Otherwise:
        Note: Emit values
        Let values be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "values"
        If values is not equal to 0:
            Let value_count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with values
            Let i be 0

            While i is less than value_count:
                Let value be proc get_list_item from ListOps with values, i
                If value is not equal to 0:
                    proc generate_node with context, value
                    If i is less than value_count minus 1:
                        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
                    End If
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
    End If

    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Note: Emit statements for this WHEN clause
    Let statements be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "statements"
    If statements is not equal to 0:
        Let stmt_count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with statements
        Set i to 0

        Note: Increment indent for WHEN statements
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, indent_level plus 1

        While i is less than stmt_count:
            Let stmt be proc get_list_item from ListOps with statements, i
            If stmt is not equal to 0:
                proc generate_node with context, stmt
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Note: Restore indent
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with context, 8, indent_level
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
PERFORM is the COBOL primitive for invoking a paragraph as a sub-routine.
The target paragraph name is captured by the HIR layer and emitted verbatim.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads "target" from the HIR dictionary and emits "PERFORM <target>." indented
one level past the current depth.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_perform_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate PERFORM statement

    @Reasoning:
    PERFORM paragraph-name or PERFORM UNTIL condition.
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "PERFORM"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter

    Let target be proc get_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "target"
    If target is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, target
    End If

    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
DISPLAY is COBOL's print statement. Multiple items are concatenated with
spaces on a single output line.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "DISPLAY ", then iterates the "items" HIR list dispatching each item
via generate_node with spaces between consecutive items. Closes with period
and newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_display_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate DISPLAY statement

    @Reasoning:
    DISPLAY item1 item2 ...
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "DISPLAY"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter

    Let items be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "items"

    If items is not equal to 0:
        Let count be proc get_list_length from ListOps with items
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than count:
            Let item be proc get_list_item from ListOps with items, i
            proc generate_node with context, item

            If i plus 1 is less than count:
                proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
ACCEPT reads from STDIN (or system data) into a named destination. Single
destination per statement so no list iteration is needed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "ACCEPT " then recurses on the "destination" HIR node before writing
period + newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_accept_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate ACCEPT statement

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "ACCEPT"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter

    Let destination be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "destination"
    If destination is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_node with context, destination
    End If

    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
GO TO is COBOL's unconditional jump. Even modern style guides accept it for
exception/error exit blocks, so the backend must emit it faithfully.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads "target" string from the HIR dictionary and emits "GO TO <target>."
followed by a newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_goto_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate GO TO statement

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "GO TO"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter

    Let target be proc get_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "target"
    If target is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, target
    End If

    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
STOP RUN terminates a COBOL program and returns control to the OS. Always
takes the full "STOP RUN" form to disambiguate from variant constructs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "STOP RUN." at the appropriate indent followed by a newline. No data
fields are consulted from the HIR node.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_stop_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate STOP statement

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "STOP RUN"
    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
EXIT marks the formal end of a paragraph; commonly used as a target for
PERFORM ... THRU to bound a procedural range.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "EXIT." at the current indent followed by a newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_exit_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate EXIT statement

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "EXIT"
    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
GOBACK returns from a sub-program, releasing control to the caller while
keeping the run-unit alive. Distinct from STOP RUN which terminates the
whole run-unit.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "GOBACK." at the appropriate indent followed by a newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_goback_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate GOBACK statement

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "GOBACK"
    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
CALL invokes another COBOL sub-program by name. The current emitter writes
the literal token "program-name"; the surrounding HIR pass overwrites that
placeholder with the resolved callee identifier when wiring the call graph.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "CALL program-name." at the current indent followed by a newline. The
program-name token is filled in by the HIR linker before final output.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_call_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate CALL statement

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "CALL"
    proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "program-name"
    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

Note: File I/O Generation

@Reasoning:
OPEN binds a logical file to the runtime so subsequent READ/WRITE statements
have a backing handle. The current emitter writes a canonical "OPEN INPUT
file-name" template, which the HIR linker rewrites with concrete identifiers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "OPEN INPUT file-name." at the current indent followed by a newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_open_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate OPEN statement

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "OPEN INPUT file-name"
    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
CLOSE releases a previously OPENed file handle and flushes any pending writes.
Emitted with the canonical "file-name" placeholder that the HIR linker
substitutes with concrete identifiers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "CLOSE file-name." at the current indent followed by a newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_close_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate CLOSE statement

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "CLOSE file-name"
    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
READ pulls the next record from an OPENed file into the named record buffer.
The INTO clause provides an additional destination after the implicit FD
record name.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "READ file-name INTO record." at the current indent followed by a
newline; the file and record placeholders are substituted by the HIR linker.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_read_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate READ statement

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "READ file-name INTO record"
    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
WRITE appends a record to an OPENed file. The FROM clause provides the
source buffer for the write.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "WRITE record FROM data." at the current indent followed by a newline;
record and data placeholders are substituted by the HIR linker.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_write_stmt" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate WRITE statement

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0
    Let indent_level be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 8

    proc emit_indent from Emitter with emitter, indent_level plus 1
    proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, "WRITE record FROM data"
    proc emit_period from Emitter with emitter
    proc emit_newline from Emitter with emitter

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expression Generation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
COBOL identifiers are emitted verbatim - no escaping is required because
the HIR layer already validated the name against COBOL rules.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads "name" from the HIR dictionary and writes it through emit_string. A
missing name leaves no output, which is the responsibility of the caller's
HIR validation.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_identifier" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate identifier

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    Let name be proc get_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "name"
    If name is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, name
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
COBOL literal nodes carry their textual form (numeric literal or quoted
string) directly; the HIR layer ensures quoting is correct so the emitter
can pass the bytes through.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads "value" from the HIR dictionary and writes it through emit_string.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_literal" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate literal

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    Let value be proc get_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "value"
    If value is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, value
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Binary arithmetic expressions appear inside COMPUTE; the COBOL operator
syntax matches conventional infix so a generic "left op right" emitter
suffices for +, -, *, /, **.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Recurses on the "left" child, emits the operator string with surrounding
spaces, then recurses on the "right" child. The operator string itself is
provided by the HIR node, not derived here.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_arithmetic_expr" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate arithmetic expression

    @Reasoning:
    Arithmetic expression: left operator right
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    Let left be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "left"
    If left is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_node with context, left
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
    End If

    Let operator be proc get_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "operator"
    If operator is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, operator
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
    End If

    Let right be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "right"
    If right is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_node with context, right
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Relational expressions live inside IF/EVALUATE conditions; the same generic
left-op-right layout works because COBOL supports =, >, <, >=, <=, NOT in
infix form.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Recurses on "left", emits the operator string with surrounding spaces, then
recurses on "right". The operator is selected by the HIR layer.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_relational_expr" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate relational expression

    @Reasoning:
    Relational expression: left operator right
    @End Reasoning

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    Let left be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "left"
    If left is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_node with context, left
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
    End If

    Let operator be proc get_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "operator"
    If operator is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, operator
        proc emit_space from Emitter with emitter
    End If

    Let right be proc get_dict_hir_value from Dict with hir, "right"
    If right is not equal to 0:
        proc generate_node with context, right
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
COBOL figurative constants (SPACES, ZEROS, HIGH-VALUES, LOW-VALUES,
QUOTES) are named keywords rather than literals, so they must be emitted
without quotes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads "constant" from the HIR dictionary and emits the keyword unchanged.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_figurative_const" takes context as Integer, hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate figurative constant

    Let emitter be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with context, 0

    Let constant be proc get_dict_string_value from Dict with hir, "constant"
    If constant is not equal to 0:
        proc emit_string from Emitter with emitter, constant
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Utility Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The COBOL HIR dispatcher needs an inline string-equality check; pulling in
the full StringCore equality helper would force a wider import surface and
slow link time, so this module ships its own minimal comparator.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two null-pointer fast paths (both null = equal, exactly one null = unequal),
followed by a string_length comparison and a byte-by-byte char loop using
string_char_at. Returns 1 on equality, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_equals" takes str1 as Integer, str2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Compare two strings for equality

    @Reasoning:
    Simple string comparison for HIR node type checking.
    @End Reasoning

    If str1 is equal to 0:
        If str2 is equal to 0:
            Return 1
        End If
        Return 0
    End If

    If str2 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let len1 be proc string_length from StringCore with str1
    Let len2 be proc string_length from StringCore with str2

    If len1 is not equal to len2:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than len1:
        Let char1 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with str1, i
        Let char2 be proc string_char_at from StringCore with str2, i

        If char1 is not equal to char2:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: End of HIR to COBOL Backend
